Beyond the Spec: What it Takes to Deploy UALink at Rack Scale

Good afternoon. My name is Chris Peterson. I am a fellow at Astera Labs, and we are going to talk about how the ecosystem is evolving with UALink and how to deploy it quickly and efficiently. My name is Ahmad Danesh; I run product management at Astera Labs, and I am excited to discuss work we have been doing with ecosystem partners over roughly the past year to advance UALink.

We start with what a truly open, purpose-built scale-up stack needs. First, we need a strong protocol: TCO- and performance-optimized, built for scale-up from performance, reliability, and scalability angles. UALink is that protocol, and we go deeper in each area. The solution must scale from components to switch trays to the full rack. It must be deployable, with rack management from tray through pod controllers and the software needed to operate it. After deployment, operators need maximal utilization and application uptime, with RAS that supports that. In multi-tenant settings, data privacy is critical, and UALink already defines directions that can keep advancing. Finally, for time-to-market, interoperability is required so the ecosystem can move fast while staying reliable.

The UALink Consortium launched in October 2024; work began earlier. Soon after, the 1.0 specification delivered bandwidth and latency alongside silicon efficiency (power and area) for strong performance per watt. The next generation of the specification targets more performance, in-network compute style capabilities, and lower power per bit.

Delivering a full rack requires chips—retimers and switches—and accelerator partners integrating UALink. Beyond silicon, we need full platforms: compute trays and switch trays, reference designs that stay open and interchangeable across vendors, and full UALink 200G racks built on OCP collaboration, pushing cable backplane approaches and pod controllers that reuse and extend existing infrastructure.

Chris turns to software integration. With IP available today and silicon and boards following, rack integration needs three elements: a UALink pod controller, a node management agent, and a switch management agent. The pod controller discovers, identifies, and configures scale-up fabric components—XPUs and switches—assigns identifiers and virtual pod (V-pod) configuration, and acts as the management entry for the rack. It typically runs where rack management already exists: a top-of-rack box, a VM on a host, or another cluster-level orchestration point.

Compute trays host XPUs that need configuration. A node management agent usually runs on the BMC, adding capability so XPUs enroll correctly, join the right V-pod, and maintain isolation and IDs. On switch trays, a switch management agent may run on a BMC in OpenBMC or on a compute module with an NOS such as Sonic. It talks to switches through OCP’s SAI interface, extended for UALink so existing tooling can configure the fabric. A dedicated session the following afternoon covers management in more depth.

RAS is broad; at a high level, UALink inherits expected behaviors: link-level protection such as CRC and FEC from existing standards, data link layer retry, end-to-end data protection, and handling of link-down. For transport-level failures, UALink defines transaction-layer drop, originator drop at the UPLI, and isolation mode to quarantine a link during diagnosis. Error-injection hooks and notification paths to management (for example the pod controller) close the loop for remediation and replacement.

Security matters in cloud-like partitions. UALink uses virtual pods so XPUs map to tenants, with a lightweight AES-GCM-style mechanism in 1.0: payloads can be encrypted end-to-end through the fabric with optional authentication tags.

Interoperability starts before silicon: IP verification, emulation, and VIP work across vendors. When silicon ships, any XPU with any switch remains a core goal; the Consortium’s compliance program is slated for launch next year with broad coverage.

Ahmad closes: success takes protocol, platforms, software, RAS, and interoperability. Astera Labs focuses on scale-up switches and retiming with partners, targeting availability next year and broad deployability around 2027. Contributors can join the Consortium, read the specifications, follow OCP and UALink partnerships, or talk to the team at the event. Thank you.
